        "Diagnostic Summary: The patient is a 67-year-old male with a past medical history of depression and gout who presented with four weeks of worsening sharp epigastric and RUQ abdominal pain. He was diagnosed with acute cholecystitis and associated mild pancreatitis. At the time of discharge, his abdominal pain had resolved, and his pancreatitis had clinically subsided.\n\nLab/Imaging Highlights: Initial laboratory evaluation at an outside facility was significant for leukocytosis (WBC 17), transaminitis (ALT 178, AST 127, Tbili 2.8), and a markedly elevated lipase (1412). Admission labs at the treating facility showed a WBC of 11.5 and a lipase of 129. RUQ ultrasound demonstrated gallbladder sludge and a 4mm polyp without stones. A subsequent MRCP was critical in the diagnosis, showing mild pancreatitis, common bile duct dilation to 1.1 cm (without choledocholithiasis), and gallbladder wall thickening and enhancement concerning for acute cholecystitis. By discharge, labs had normalized with a WBC of 7.3 and improving transaminases.\n\nClinical Procedures: The patient was initially managed conservatively with bowel rest, aggressive intravenous hydration, and intravenous antibiotics (Cefoxitin, followed by Ciprofloxacin and Metronidazole). Once the pancreatitis stabilized, he underwent an uncomplicated laparoscopic cholecystectomy on hospital day 3. Post-operatively, his diet was successfully advanced, and a concurrent gout flare in his right great toe was managed with colchicine and his home allopurinol regimen.\n\nComprehensive Discharge Summary: Mr. ___ is a 67-year-old male discharged following a laparoscopic cholecystectomy for cholecystitis. His hospital course included the management of mild gallstone pancreatitis and a gout flare. He was discharged in stable condition on postoperative day 1 with a regular diet, instructions for activity restriction (no heavy lifting >10 lbs for 6 weeks), and a plan for follow-up in the general surgery clinic in 1-2 weeks. Medications at discharge include oxycodone and acetaminophen for pain management, stool softeners, and his chronic home medications.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
